Tutorial

Use Ollama 🦙 as your Local AI Assistant on the CLI

6 steps

In this tutorial, you will be able to explore ollama, to get up and running large language models locally. You will know how to install and run ollama for the first time. Once done, you will be able to know what you can do with it such as using other pre-trained models made by various organisations such as Microsoft’s phi and phi3 models, and Meta’s llama2 and llama3.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

nil

Learning Outcomes

  • Run other models from other providers with ollama
  • Use ollama as a productivity tool

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 6

  • Step 1: What is Ollama🦙?

    Ollama is a local AI assistant designed to be used on Command Line Interface (CLI). It makes your daily tasks more efficient by providing instant solutions. Whether you are a programmer, data scientist, or just a tech enthusiast, Ollama is a handy tool that can help you navigate your technical tasks with ease.

  • Step 2: Installation

    Head to https://ollama.com/download/. Follow the install instructions. OR you can install it through your system’s package manager, for example:

    • Windows: winget install Ollama.Ollama
    • Linux (openSUSE, ArchLinux, Ubuntu): as root run sudo zypper in ollama, sudo pacman -S ollama, sudo apt install ollama . This might not be enough. See Additional information for Linux users.
    • MacOS: brew install ollama

    If you are using other package managers, please check your package repository if ollama exists. Otherwise, you can still use the download instructions from their website.

    Additional Information for Linux Users

    For Linux users, please proceed to your distro’s documentation in installing the necessary GPU drivers. Although, you can still run the models but through the CPU which can be power draining and slowing down the output generation.

    The manual way

    If your distro does not ship ollama, you can head over to https://github.com/ollama/ollama/blob/main/docs/linux.md#adding-ollama-as-a-startup-service-recommended. Follow the instructions and adapt to whatever distro you are using to install the GPU drivers.

    The distro-provided way

    If your distro ships ollama, you can just install it and the GPU drivers (if available) from the distro’s package manager. For example, if you have an openSUSE Tumbleweed system and own an NVIDIA driver, do the following commands

    sudo zypper addrepo -p 100 https://developer.download.nvidia.com/compute/cuda/repos/opensuse15/x86_64/  cuda
sudo zypper addrepo -p 100 https://download.nvidia.com/opensuse/tumbleweed NVIDIA
sudo zypper ref -f  # say yes to trust always the newly added repos
# installs nvidia drivers through device hardware detection
sudo zypper install-new-recommends --repo NVIDIA  # say yes to all license agreements
# installs the cuda runtime
sudo zypper install --recommends cuda  # say yes to all license agreements
# runs ollama server as a systemd service. persists after reboot. 
# warning: huge download size
# please provide root password to polkit prompt 
# or add `sudo` before the command
systemctl enable --now ollama.service
# Bug not yet merged in the openSUSE repos
# https://github.com/ollama/ollama/pull/2838
# Without this, you can't use the GPU. REBOOT after.
sudo usermod -a -G video ollama

    Confirm that your NVIDIA GPU and CUDA is working by running

    nvidia-smi
/usr/local/cuda-12.4/extras/demo_suite/deviceQuery

    You will see a similar output for the second command as shown below.

  • Step 3: Running it the first time

    To run ollama the first time, you can use the following command. For this session, llama3 model as of this moment has a size of ~4.7GB. The model will be first downloaded.

    ollama run llama3

    This will run the ollama prompt locally. You can try “talking” to it by saying hi.

    Other commands are shown by typing and entering /? . These commands are self-explanatory.

    To use other models e.g. llama2, you can run ollama run <name of model>.

    A list of available models are in this link https://github.com/ollama/ollama?tab=readme-ov-file#model-library or this link https://ollama.com/library. 

    To download a model to be used later, you can use ollama pull <name of model>. 

    To get a list of versions or tags you can use, head to https://ollama.com/library. Then go select a from a list of models. Lastly, select tags and you can see the list from there.

    🚧Do note the size of each model to download. 

    Some model versions or tags are named differently but are actually the same. You will know this because of the hash.

    To specify the version or tag of a model to pull or run, you can use 

    ollama pull <name of model>:<version or tag>

    Replace pull with run if you want to run it immediately after download.

  • Step 4: What can you do with Ollama?

    Local AI assistant tool for productivity tasks

    Helps you study. Maybe you have issues with your Physics class?

    Do remember to verify its output because the data provided to the model might not be accurate from time to time.

    Help formulate better sentence structure and grammar. Maybe you want to write an invite for a birthday party before sending it through email?

    Maybe English isn’t your native language.

    Help translate foreign languages to another language. Maybe your friend wants to meet with you but you have a language barrier.

    🧠 Other things you can do with it are explained in the next step.

  • Step 5: API Experimentation

    ollama runs a local server on your computer to serve the API and receive API requests.

    On Linux, you can see this with journalctl -u ollama if you have installed or created a systemd service for ollama as shown below

    One can use curl to communicate with the local server just like how you do it inside a prompt. But instead of a prompt, you have to provide a JSON string and you will receive also an output in a form of a JSON string. 

    The JSON output string can have more keys and values you can use to adjust the output and to insert additional parameters:

    • model - name of the model to use e.g. llama3 or phi3
    • prompt - a string that represents user input e.g. “Hi there!”
    • stream - whether to have each output e.g. word/phrase/token generated as multiple JSON objects or a single JSON object. Default is true.
    • format - specifies format. Can only be JSON or raw text. The value of the response is a JSON instead of a generated “message”.

    The JSON string can be sent using the curl command to the API server

     curl http://localhost:11434/api/generate -d '{
  "model": "llama3",
  "prompt": "Who are you?",
  "stream": true,
  "options": {
    "num_keep": 5,
    "seed": 42,
    "use_mmap": true,
    "use_mlock": false,
    "num_thread": 8
  }
}'
    Bash

    The JSON response string can look like multiples of JSON objects.

    {"model":"llama3","created_at":"2024-05-19T10:01:38.27234044Z","response":"I","done":false}
{"model":"llama3","created_at":"2024-05-19T10:01:38.501091032Z","response":" am","done":false}
    JSON

    Since ollama has an API, this also means that in the future, you can start exploring how to integrate the API such as creating a simple AI chatbot where you can select options to, for example, choose either llama3 or phi3 as the pre-trained model.

  • Step 6: Conclusion

    In conclusion, ollama provides a powerful, local AI solution that can be used for a wide range of tasks. Whether you are studying, need help with language translation, or want to integrate AI into your projects, ollama offers a flexible and easy-to-use tool. With its extensive model library and the ability to run your own models, the possibilities are endless. Start exploring ollama today and unlock the potential of AI right on your local machine.
